article.headline: Princeton 70, Yale 58
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Judson Wallace scored 29 points as Princeton erased a 14-point first-half deficit and pulled away from Yale 70-58 Friday night. The win kept the Tigers (14-7) in first place in the Ivy League at 7-1, a half-game ahead of Brown, which beat Penn. The Quakers fell two games behind the Tigers with six to play. Yale dropped to 9-13 overall, 4-5 in league. Wallace connected on 11 of 12 shots from the field to record his third straight 20-plus point game. The Tigers broke a 44-44 tie by going on an 18-4 streak to build a 62-48 advantage, capping it with a Scott Greenman three-pointer with 5:15 left and the shot clock winding down. The Tigers went on a 23-4 spurt spanning the first and second halves to take a 44-39 lead as Yale hit just one field goal in 10 minutes. Princeton got back into the game by scoring the last seven points of the first half, led by Will Venable. The junior sank a three to answer one by Yale's Alex Gamboa and then drove past his defender for a layup in the lane. Venable then made a steal with 4 seconds to go in the half and dropped in a floater just as the buzzer sounded, cutting the deficit to 35-28 at the half. Yale put together a 21-7 run to break a 14-14 tie earlier by getting a lot of easy baskets on fast breaks or on drives for layups. Wallace led all scorers with 11 points in the first half for the Tigers.
